Crypto’s Reprogramming: The Propagation of Agents Across Sectors

Andrew Dyer
Kinji Steimetz
Chris Davis

Jan 10, 2025 ⋅  15 min read

“AI agents is probably the next robotics industry and likely to be a multi-trillion dollar opportunity.” - Jensen Huang
“We are now confident we know how to build AGI as we have traditionally understood it. We believe that, in 2025, we may see the first AI agents “join the workforce” and materially change the output of companies. We continue to believe that iteratively putting great tools in the hands of people leads to great, broadly-distributed outcomes.” - Sam Altman

We’ve only scratched the surface for what impact LLMs will have on the consumer and enterprise fronts. Both closed and open-source models will continue to rapidly improve in the coming year through the brute force of more compute and technical advancements in implementation. We know that the end state of this new technology is not just chatbots, research assistants, or summary generators. It is more likely on a trajectory toward something like Artificial Super Intelligence.

But baby steps first. Before we reach OpenAI’s Level 5 - AI that can replace entire organizations - we will need to have specialized agents that dominate individual workflows within companies. Based on Langbase’s State of AI Agents survey, workflows within software development, marketing, and IT will likely be targeted first. The low-hanging fruit for this first wave of agents is a combination of automating repetitive administrative tasks and providing productivity-enhancing tools for skilled laborers like programmers. Jensen Huang revealed Nvidia’s initial foray into agents at the CES Keynote with their "AI Blueprints.” Developers can already use NVIDIA microservices to create AI agents for tasks like fraud detection, customer service, and supply chain optimization.

Within crypto, however, we have already seen an explosion of experimentation with agents across very different verticals. Users on VIRTUALS have launched more than 13,000 agents on the platform, and showcase agents using other frameworks like RIG are set to be revealed soon. While the majority of agents thus far have been interactive characters or social media personas, we have also seen agents that: excel at token quant work, bet on sports, and run their own investment funds. Agents are infiltrating DeFi front-ends, metaverse worlds, and gaming initiatives. This leads us to a few questions:

  • How will agents impact both the more battle-tested sectors like DeFi and those that never fully took off like Gaming?
  • Are the perceived benefits of agents more hype than substance?
  • Which early, stand-out agents (or agentic apps) are positioned to accrue the most value, and what might they have in common?

Andrew - @0xSynthesis1

Revamping Failed Narratives - Agents in the Metaverse

After Meta’s failed bets on virtual worlds - totaling some $25 billion in losses in 2021 and 2022 - investor appetite for anything metaverse-related has largely vanished. Within crypto, older metaverse platforms like Decentraland and The Sandbox were plagued by low DAUs, which made in-game worlds feel sparse and desolate. Do agents have any shot on refreshing this troubled vertical?

Hyperfy is one metaverse platform that is taking an agent-centric approach to building virtual worlds. They provide an SDK and other tooling so that users with limited coding experience can create 3D worlds like galleries, music venues, storefronts, games, etc. Users can also drag and drop their own images, videos, audio, 2D/3D NFTs into the worlds they create, or purchase pre-created worlds from other users. On the agent-front, Hyperfy is partnering with ai16z for a deep integration with the Eliza framework so that Eliza agents can get 3D avatars and operate autonomously as characters within these game worlds. We see a few ways the overlap between agent tech and virtual worlds might create better outcomes versus 2021:

  • Agents may fix a cold-start problem for a lot of these platforms that are inherently social and require a steady user-base to be fun and engaging. Agents that can operate and interact with both environments and users like actual people, not just NPCs, create richer worlds around the clock.
  • Tooling that can easily turn prompts into environments or agents themselves within worlds can unlock new content creation from players and developers who have more limited experience. Agents themselves may become primary creators and maintainers of new virtual worlds.
  • As the VIRTUALS team mentioned with their playable Westworld demo, introducing agents into any world creates potentially infinite replayability. Agents that can conduct complex tasks, generate in-game items, and cooperate with users can create vastly more engaging gameplay versus the platforms of yesteryear.

Skepticism to the sector more broadly is certainly warranted given the empty promises of last cycle. But it is definitely an area to watch as it may uniquely benefit from the agent value-proposition.

Sam - @CryptoSam01

DeFAI Gaining Momentum: Innovations, Opportunities, and the Path Ahead

Crypto has been buzzing about DeFAI this past week since several projects adopted the moniker. In a recent article, Danielle Cesta underscores the current limitations of DeFi and explores how AI-driven agentic properties could transform crypto’s user experience by minimizing the need for human interaction onchain.

The Trajectory of DeFAI: Lessons from DeFi’s Evolution

“I very frequently get the question: 'What's going to change in the next 10 years?' And that is a very interesting question; it's a very common one. I almost never get the question: 'What's not going to change in the next 10 years?' And I submit to you that that second question is actually the more important of the two -- because you can build a business strategy around the things that are stable in time.” - Jeff Bezos

What might the evolution of DeFAI look like? History suggests the trajectory will echo patterns seen in other sectors. During the rise of DeFi, there was an explosion of similar protocols (e.g., Uniswap forks) before innovations like Curve and Yearn Finance stood out. Users initially flocked to farm high APYs, only to pivot toward projects like OlympusDAO that offered even higher yields. DeFAI’s journey could follow a similar progression.

Though many look indistinguishable, we’ve seen a surge in new trading and alpha-focused agents. Platforms that enable users to interact with AI agents through intuitive commands (AKA natural language interfaces) emerged as the attention winner after the Solana AI Hackathon. Yet, we’ve already seen several AI platforms effectively performing the same simple actions. The commoditization of AI protocols is becoming clear even quicker than DeFi, so expect the same for DeFAI. The question remains: what next, and how do you find a diamond in the rough?

Building the Ecosystem: Routes, Tools, and Innovation

Moats look thinner in DeFAI than in other sectors. Still, I’d argue some of the more important signals look similar: developer velocity, deep feature and protocol integration, and quality infrastructure.

First-mover advantages have been important for AI, especially in the context of Virtuals, ai16z, and Griffain, but even Render with distributed compute. I’d argue that the advantage extends to feature integrations as well, whether in the UI/UX or deep integrations in key DeFi protocols. I’m paying attention to some of the key natural language interfaces and what blue-chip DeFi protocols they land as partners.

Users will want ways to enhance and customize their agents, such as plugins and extensions. Think of a "Plugin Store" where users can purchase tools to enable advanced functionalities like high-frequency trading, cross-chain swaps, liquidity pool creation, sniping, and farming. For DeFAI protocols like HeyAnon, Griffain, Orbit, or Neur, I’m more interested in their ability to create independent frameworks that cater to popular DeFi protocols and activities (i.e., a yield farming agent on Raydium, a meme sniper on pump.fun, or a token insights bot that queries DefiLlama or Messari). Feature and protocol integration is vague, but DeFAI protocols that are well connected in DeFi will accrue value from two sides: account abstraction through agents and DeFi activity.

Beyond agents, agentic frameworks, and launchpads, agents will need infrastructure that supports mobility and trading. The current leaders in DeFAI are fleshing out their own infrastructure via liquidity and DeFi integrations, but projects like Wayfinder are developing routing mechanisms for any agent to facilitate efficient AI interactions across chains and DeFi protocols. The project, nicknamed Wayfinder Graph, could look like Google for AI, operating as the blockchain search engine for our agents. Similar to ai16z or Virtuals, Wayfinder’s approach relies on the ecosystem adopting its framework and philosophy.

Ultimately, DeFAI only succeeds if anyone can use it or if there’s more money to be made using agents. I’d argue both are still possible and may succeed concurrently, but defining how DeFAI protocols succeed seems more critical than which if you want to be proactive.

Chris - @capradavis

As we begin sobering up from the euphoria of the AI agent honeymoon phase, the "quiet part" is beginning to creep into the market’s consciousness: Does this need to be onchain?

As is often the case, it depends.

Most social media-based agents’ interaction with the blockchain begins and ends with the deployment of their token. There’s nothing inherently wrong with this—tokens are fun. However, I’d categorize many of these projects as more hype than substance. On the other hand, DefAI projects, like the ones Sam mentioned above, can enable valuable onchain autonomous actions, such as portfolio management. That said, I agree with Kinji that these agents are unlikely to outperform proprietary agents developed by entities with access to robust data pipelines.

So, where can agents truly push the frontiers of blockchain technology? I’d argue one promising area is fully onchain games (FOCGs).

Games

Video games are a useful medium for training AI. They offer environments that compel agents to navigate uncertainty, adapt to new situations in real-time, and make concrete decisions to achieve their objectives. For years, prominent AI organizations like OpenAI and DeepMind have used video games as testing grounds to push the boundaries of their development and unlock innovations. Conversely, games have also reaped benefits from the advancements driven by AI.

Incorporating agents into games—whether Web2 or Web3—offers numerous benefits for both players and developers:

  • Increased Player Liquidity: A high availability of active players mitigates experiences that contribute to churn, such as long match wait times, lack of social interaction, or stagnant in-game economies. This allows developers to focus on competing through gameplay elements without being hindered by player acquisition bottlenecks.
  • Higher Quality NPC Relationships: Dynamic NPC interactions create more engaging experiences and foster emotional connections with the game, ideally increasing player retention.
  • Engaging Replayability: Autonomous NPCs reacting to achieve their goals provide a fresh experience with each run-through of quests, boss battles, or training, making gameplay consistently engaging and unpredictable.

Projects like ARC Agents by ArenaX Labs and GAME by Virtuals are frameworks at the forefront of this innovation in Web3. However, despite the immense value these projects provide, this value, in its current form, is less a blockchain-enabled innovation and more a variation on Web2 agent integrations. While ARC leverages blockchain to create incentive structures for training and enable agent ownership, the agents themselves are not interacting onchain. Similarly, the integrations with Virtuals observed thus far have involved games utilizing their framework for offchain NPC development.

Without a value proposition uniquely enabled by blockchain, projects are compelled to compete against Web2 companies with significant economies of scale. In this case, AI agents developed for these use cases compete on quality with similar technologies emerging from DeepMind and NVIDIA, which have access to vast amounts of proprietary training data. However, NVIDIA and DeepMind are not in the business of bringing agents onchain—and here lies an opportunity to create novel value.

Infinite Games

FOCGs provide an environment where agents can directly monetize their intelligence, accelerate their development, and contribute to the expansion of games:

  • Autonomous Revenue Generation: Agents can generate revenue through various in-game activities, such as setting up businesses, winning high-stakes PvP matches, or exploiting market arbitrage opportunities. Hypothetically, this revenue could be split with token holders, creating a concrete value accrual mechanism.
  • Increased Learning Capabilities: Since the game’s state and logic are stored onchain and accessible to agents, game data can be reliably queried to refine strategies and improve outcomes. Additionally, this information can be shared among agents to enhance the collective intelligence of the game’s agent economy.
  • Agent-Generated Content: Agents can autonomously produce code that contributes to gameplay development. This helps address the “cold start” problem of attracting enough developer interest to ignite a user-generated content flywheel, where better gameplay attracts more players, attracting more developers who create better gameplay.

These value propositions are uniquely enabled by onchain primitives. Combined with the broader benefits of agent integration, they establish a strong symbiotic onchain relationship between agents, players, and developers.

Looking Ahead

Multiple projects are working toward this vision. Most notably, in late December, "Loaf," a founder of the onchain gaming infrastructure provider Cartridge, announced his project, Daydream Protocol. Daydream can be integrated into popular Web3 agent frameworks like Eliza, functioning as a plug-in that enables developers to deploy onchain gaming agents capable of performing virtually any onchain in-game action.

The timing for this innovation is right. Games like Pirate Nation have demonstrated that FOCGs can rival the UX of partially onchain games, Web3 gamers are increasingly drawn to high-stakes FOCGs like Cambria, and agent technology has become a central focus of discussions surrounding AI. While it may take a while for a breakout FOCG featuring AI agents to emerge, I believe this foundational period will be regarded in hindsight as pivotal for the future of gaming.

Kinji - @SteimetzKinji

My take for 2025 is that AI agents will peak in Q1 and fail to sustain their momentum, driven by an overly optimistic market narrative. Many compare the AI agent trend to DeFi Summer or the alt-layer 1 trade, but I believe these comparisons are flawed. Both DeFi and alt-layer 1s had a clear path to becoming secular winners—establishing onchain use cases that outcompete offchain alternatives. I don’t see the same potential for onchain agent platforms.

Onchain and Open-source: Possible Liabilities

In my view, the most viable use cases for AI agents in crypto will exist offchain, while those requiring onchain deployments are likely to underperform offchain or centralized competitors. Offchain use cases, such as information agents like AIXBT, are finding product-market fit in aggregating and analyzing crypto-related data. However, they lack similar traction for their associated tokens. Looking at incumbents like Messari, which AIXBT aims to displace, none of these businesses operate onchain. Crypto research firms publish offchain, provide data through traditional APIs, and collect payments via traditional systems. While tokens tied to agentic platforms can gain attention, meaningful capital allocation requires a fundamental value accrual narrative. Without it, tokens risk becoming purely meme-driven plays, where stronger memes inevitably outperform (hot air rises).

Another cited use case for AI agents is executing onchain actions for users, such as autonomous portfolio management. Here, outperformance is the only metric that matters, and I find it unlikely that open-source agents will outperform closed-source ones. Success in this space will depend on fine-tuning models and leveraging diversified, proprietary data pipelines. Specialized advisors will likely guard their proprietary models and data to sustain outperformance, revealing their methodologies only after the competitive advantage has faded. This mirrors how quantitative hedge funds operate: they exploit every ounce of outperformance privately rather than sharing it with the market. As a result, we’re more likely to see specialized financial services firms building in-house, black-box agents and receiving onchain, non-custodial deposits, rather than open-source agents dominating capital flows.

There are other potential use cases for AI agents, but most fall into two categories: being outcompeted by offchain entities or relying on growth in other sectors. For instance, coding agents that assist developers with writing applications don’t gain much from being onchain and will likely be dominated by offchain companies. Gaming agents could see some utilization, but their success hinges on onchain gaming finding product-market fit—a gamble I’m not convinced will pay off. Betting on these agents is essentially betting that they will unlock the potential of onchain gaming or the metaverse, which I find unlikely. I’m not planning to dive into the metaverse just to interact with agentic NPCs.

Markets, in my view, have barely scratched the surface of evaluating the future of an agent-driven economy. The prevalence of AI agents or onchain bots doesn’t guarantee that current protocols will become secular winners. Digging deeper, the open-source nature of many of these platforms is more of a liability than an asset, likely leading to declining performance. While the future may be agentic, it won’t look anything like what markets currently expect.

Dylan - @dylangbane

Decentralized Physical Artificial Intelligence Networks (DePAIN)

While early in AI agent development, most value may ultimately accrue to the physical layer interacting with the real world. AI agent software will operate robots, autonomous vehicles, and other machines, overcoming the last frontier of AI's integration with the world.

Advances enabling real,world agents may come much faster from crypto than Web2 due to the proliferation of DePIN combined with the current AI agent craze. Agents can leverage DePIN sensors, robots, and coordination mechanisms to interact with the real world and operate physical infrastructure. Such a vision has been outlined by L1s like Peaq in their machine economy thesis and spatial compute networks like Auki which conceptualize “DePIN as AGI reaching back in time and building itself,” leveraging sensors and other infrastructure needed for AI to interact with the real world.

A novel acronym, DePAIN (Decentralized Physical Artificial Intelligence Networks), has emerged to describe the infrastructure needed to support real-world AI agents. Such networks require AI agent software, physical infrastructure for data collection, and physical infrastructure operated by AI agents. DePAIN networks appear closer to fruition than originally anticipated. On January 9th, IoTeX announced a partnership with Eliza Labs, the foundation behind ai16z, to integrate IoTeX’s DePIN network with ElizaOS. The integration allows Eliza-based agents to access real-time data from IoTeX’s sensors, control DePIN infrastructure, and ultimately allow agents to interact with the real world. AI agents will have access to Nubila’s weather network, GEODNET’s RTK correction network, and Pebble Tracker’s data collection capabilities at the outset.

Access to real--related robotics projects in the public view, ample opportunity exists to build in this space and leverage agent frameworks to create decentralized AI-world data through DePINs differentiates Eliza agents connected to this data, potentially pointing to the next stage of the AI agent craze. In particular, DePIN robots operated by Eliza agents could stand to be an interesting use case. While Frodobots and Xmaquina are the only DePIN related robotics projects in the public view, ample opportunity exists to build in this space and leverage agent frameworks to create decentralized AI operated robots that could compete with centralized agent providers.

Stay tuned for further Messari Research on DePAIN and physical AI agents.

Also, check out our exploration of the spatial computing- and data needed to power DePAIN networks in the State of DePIN 2024.
